1 (b) For a multicounty Case Review Multidisciplinary Team, the director of each local
2 department of social services represented in the multicounty team has the powers and duties
3 enumerated in subsection (a) of this section.
4 "§ 108A-118.5. Case Review Multidisciplinary Team; DHHS responsibility for training
5 team members.
6 The Department of Health and Human Services shall develop and make available for the
7 members of each Case Review Multidisciplinary Team, on an ongoing basis, training materials
8 that address all of the following:
9 (1) An overview of adult protective services law and policy.
10 (2) The role and function of a Case Review Multidisciplinary Team.
11 (3) Case Review Multidisciplinary Team confidentiality requirements.
12 (4) Case Review Multidisciplinary Team record-keeping requirements.
13 "§ 108A-118.6. Case Review Multidisciplinary Team; information sharing.
14 (a) Except as prohibited by federal law and notwithstanding any other State law to the
15 contrary, any member of a Case Review Multidisciplinary Team may disclose to other members
16 of the Case Review Multidisciplinary Team any information in the member's possession that is
17 relevant to any of the following:
18 (1) Performing reviews of selected active cases in which disabled adults or older
19 adults are being served by adult protective services through local departments
20 of social services.
21 (2) Providing, arranging, or coordinating services on behalf of disabled adults or
22 older adults whose cases have been or are currently under review by the Case
23 Review Multidisciplinary Team.
24 (b) The local director of social services shall not share any information that discloses the
25 identity of individuals who have reported suspected abuse, neglect, or exploitation of a disabled
26 adult or older adult to the local department of social services, except as allowed by State or federal
27 law.
28 (c) Meetings of the Case Review Multidisciplinary Team are not subject to the provisions
29 of Article 33C of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes.
30 (d) The authority of a Case Review Multidisciplinary Team to disclose information
31 pursuant to this section terminates when a case is no longer an active case in which a disabled
32 adult or older adult is being served by adult protective services through a local department of
33 social services, including if the inactive status of the case is due to the disabled adult's or older
34 adult's failure to give consent to receive protective services or due to the disabled adult's or older
35 adult's withdrawal of consent to receive protective services.
36 "§ 108A-118.7. Case Review Multidisciplinary Team; confidentiality of records and
37 information; rules.
38 (a) All information and records acquired or generated by a Case Review
39 Multidisciplinary Team during its existence and in the exercise of its duties are confidential and
40 may be disclosed only as necessary to carry out the purposes of the Case Review
41 Multidisciplinary Team as described in this Article or as otherwise permitted by State or federal
42 law. This subsection does not preclude a court of competent jurisdiction from compelling the
43 disclosure of any information or records acquired or generated by a Case Review
44 Multidisciplinary Team if, in the court's opinion, disclosure is necessary to a proper
45 administration of justice and disclosure is not otherwise prohibited by State or federal law.
46 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this section, information generated in a meeting of
47 a Case Review Multidisciplinary Team may be disclosed as provided in this subsection in any of
48 the following circumstances:
49 (1) To a local board of county commissioners when the Case Review
50 Multidisciplinary Team makes its annual recommendations, if any, pursuant
51 to G.S. 108A-118.3(2); provided that such recommendations shall not identify
Page 4 Senate Bill 400-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 or reveal any confidential information about individual adult protective
2 services cases reviewed by the Case Review Multidisciplinary Team.
3 (2) To a local board of social services by the director of the local department of
4 social services when reporting on the activities of the Case Review
5 Multidisciplinary Team; provided that such reports shall not identify or reveal
6 any confidential information about individual adult protective services cases
7 reviewed by the Case Review Multidisciplinary Team.
8 (3) By a member of the Case Review Multidisciplinary Team to the member's
9 agency or organization as needed to provide or arrange services for a disabled
10 adult or older adult.
11 (c) Each member of a Case Review Multidisciplinary Team is required to sign a
12 statement indicating an understanding of and adherence to the confidentiality requirements of
13 this section, including the consequences of any breach of confidentiality. The chair shall submit
14 a recommendation, in writing, to the appropriate appointing authority for the removal of any
15 member who fails to (i) sign the statement required by this subsection or (ii) comply with the
16 confidentiality requirements of this section.
17 (d) The local department of social services shall make an entry in the disabled adult's or
18 older adult's protective services record at the time it is selected for review by a Case Review
19 Multidisciplinary Team to indicate that it was selected for review. Additional entry into the
20 record shall be at the discretion of the director of the local department of social services.
21 (e) Nothing in this Article shall be construed to prohibit a Case Review Multidisciplinary
22 Team from sharing or accessing confidential information and records as permitted or required by
23 applicable State or federal law, including any law that permits the disclosure of confidential
24 information pursuant to the informed consent of a disabled adult or older adult or the authorized
25 representative of a disabled adult or older adult.
26 (f) The Social Services Commission may adopt rules consistent with this Article to
27 establish protocols for reviews conducted by Case Review Multidisciplinary Teams.
28 "§ 108A-118.8. Systemic Review Multidisciplinary Team allowed but not covered by this
29 Article.
30 Nothing in this Article shall be construed to prohibit a county from establishing both a Case
31 Review Multidisciplinary Team and a Systemic Review Multidisciplinary Team. However, this
32 Article applies only to a single or multicounty Case Review Multidisciplinary Team established
33 pursuant to this Article."
34 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
